===Etymology 1===
From ancient [[Greek]]: ''μέτρον'' (''metron''), "[[measure]]", "rule", "length", "size", "poetic metre"; via [[French]] ''[[mètre]]''.

====Noun====
# The basic [[unit]] of [[length]] in the [[International System of Units]] (SI: Système International d'Unités). It is defined as the [[length]] of the path travelled by [[light]] in a [[vacuum]] during a [[time]] interval of 1/299,792,458 of a [[second]]. It is equal to 39.37 [[Imperial]] [[inch]]es.
#: '''Spelling''': This, rather than ''meter'', is the spelling adopted by the International Bureau of Weights and Measures for use in its publications.
#: '''Symbol''': [[m]]
#: ''The measures of length above the metre are ten times ... greater than the metre''. (''The Monthly magazine and British register'', No. 3 1797).
#: ''A dress length of 8 metres of the best quality costs 58 francs.'' (''The Young Englishwoman'', April 1873).
#: ''The 12-metre yachts ... can be sailed efficiently with four paid hands.'' (''The Observer'', April 15 1928).

